SIMPLE: antipode
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Antipode
<hw>An"ti*pode</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One of the
antipodes; anything exactly opposite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In tale or history your beggar is ever the just
<qex>antipode</qex> to your king.</q> <rj><qau>Lamb.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The singular, <xex>antipode</xex>, is exceptional in
formation, but has been used by good writers. Its regular English plural
would be <pr><it>⟦acr⟧n"t⟦icr⟧*p⟦omac⟧des</it></pr>, the last syllable
rhyming with <it>abodes</it>, and this pronunciation is sometimes heard.
The plural form (originally a Latin word without a singular) is in
common use, and is pronounced, after the English method of Latin,
<pr><it>⟦acr⟧n*t⟦icr⟧p"⟦osl⟧*d⟦emac⟧z</it></pr>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Antipodean</ent>⟦br⟧
